\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Secure configuration of information systems is the foundation of system integrity and the principle of least functionality.
 By establishing,
 enforcing,
 and continuously monitoring approved baselines,
 ECIO minimizes the organizational attack surface and protects the confidentiality,
 integrity,
 and availability of County systems,
 with specific emphasis on environments processing Criminal Justice Information (CJI).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Baseline Configuration Establishment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall establish,
 document,
 and maintain secure configuration baselines for all Elko County information systems,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CM-2 (Baseline Configuration).
 The Assistant IT Director shall derive baselines from Defense Information Systems Agency (DISA) Security Technical Implementation Guides (STIGs).
 Where an applicable DISA STIG does not exist for a specific system class,
 the Assistant IT Director shall use the Center for Internet Security (CIS) Benchmark at Level 2 or higher as the mandatory fallback baseline standard.
 The Assistant IT Director shall document the absence of an applicable STIG and the use of the CIS fallback in the System Security Plan (SSP).
 The Assistant IT Director shall review and update these baselines at least annually,
 or upon the introduction of a new system architecture,
 to maintain alignment with the current approved release of the applicable STIG or CIS Benchmark.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall retain at least one (1) prior approved version of the baseline configuration for each system to support rollback capability,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CM-2(3) (Retention of Previous Configurations).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Network Topological Drawing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Network Administrator shall develop,
 document,
 and maintain under configuration control a current and complete topological drawing depicting the interconnectivity of the County network to criminal justice information systems and services.
 The Network Administrator shall review and update this drawing at least annually,
 upon security-relevant system changes,
 and when network components are installed or upgraded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Principle of Least Functionality and System Hardening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator and the Network Administrator shall configure each information system to provide only essential capabilities,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CM-7 (Least Functionality).
 Prior to production deployment,
 the Systems Administrator and the Network Administrator shall enable only those services,
 daemons,
 ports,
 protocols,
 and applications that are both explicitly justified in the approved System Security Plan (SSP) and authorized by the approved baseline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that systems in production at the effective date of this policy are assessed against the applicable baseline within ninety (90) days of the effective date.
 The responsible Systems Administrator or Network Administrator shall remediate non-compliant systems,
 or formally except them under Section 4 of this policy,
 within one hundred eighty (180) days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall conduct a least-functionality review of County information systems at least annually,
 upon security-relevant system changes,
 and when incidents identify unnecessary functions,
 ports,
 protocols,
 software,
 or services,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CM-7(1) (Periodic Review).
 The Systems Administrator and the Network Administrator shall remediate or formally except findings from each review under Section 4 of this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Default Account and Credential Hardening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Systems Administrator and the Network Administrator shall disable,
 rename,
 or strictly restrict all default,
 guest,
 and built-in vendor accounts before an asset is joined to the production network.
 The Systems Administrator and the Network Administrator shall change all default authentication credentials to meet current enterprise cryptographic and complexity standards prior to deployment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Configuration Change Control
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Information Operations Personnel shall not modify established configuration baselines except through the formal Change Management process defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.09"
